## The question (Joel's, verbatim spirit)

One 👍 through the pipe proves plumbing, not learning. Does the graded
`outcome` history actually change what the judge picks?

## Method

1. Reuse the production mechanics EXACTLY: judge model
   `openai-codex/gpt-5.6-sol:xhigh`, prompt file
   `skills/neat-memory-simple-prompt.md`, the same `judgePrompt`
   substitution shape from `.pi/extensions/observer/neat-memory.ts`
   (history = last 20 sent entries, candidates = compact excerpts).
   Build the bench as a standalone script (e.g.
   `.pi/extensions/observer/neat-memory-taste-bench.ts`) that reads
   production state READ-ONLY and shells the judge itself — do not
   import anything that sends.
2. Paired runs over IDENTICAL candidate pools: (A) real history with
   outcomes as-is, (B) same history with every `outcome` nulled. Also
   run (C) a synthetic-contrast arm: history unchanged except the graded
   entry's outcome flipped to `did-not-work` — with one real grade, C is
   what makes the bench informative at today's volume.
3. Repetitions: at least 5 per arm over the same pool (sol is
   nondeterministic; the delta must beat run-to-run noise). Capture
   every raw JSON verdict to files under the scratchpad or /tmp.
4. Report the selection delta: picks, scores, holds, and any wording
   shifts, A vs B vs C, with run-level tables. An honestly null delta is
   a valid finding — then state, concretely, what graded-history volume
   and composition would make this bench decisive (feeds the brief's
   latent rerun).

